# Command & Conquer Generals Zero Hour - Headless Engine Architecture Documentation

## Executive Summary

The C&C Generals Zero Hour (GeneralsMD) source code is a complex Win32-based RTS engine with clearly separated game logic and rendering layers. The codebase uses a modular architecture with subsystem initialization, making it feasible to build a headless engine by stubbing out rendering/audio components and focusing on the core GameLogic and GameEngine systems.

---

## 1. TOP-LEVEL STRUCTURE

### Directory Organization

```
cczh-source-code/
├── Generals/               # Original C&C Generals (v1.0)
│   └── Code/
│       ├── GameEngine/    # Core game logic (platform-agnostic)
│       ├── GameEngineDevice/  # Rendering/audio (platform-specific)
│       ├── Main/          # Windows entry point
│       ├── Libraries/      # Third-party dependencies
│       └── Tools/         # Development tools
│
├── GeneralsMD/            # Zero Hour expansion (MD = MajorDestruction era)
│   └── Code/              # Identical structure to Generals/
│
└── Run/                   # Output binaries directory
```

### Generals vs GeneralsMD

- **Generals**: Original game (v1.0, ~2003)
- **GeneralsMD**: Zero Hour expansion, same code structure, differences in:
  - Map data and unit templates (INI files, not source code)
  - Game balance tweaks
  - New units/buildings specific to Zero Hour

**Both share identical source code architecture.**

---

## 2. GAMEENGINE MODULES (Core Game Logic)

### Directory Structure: `Code/GameEngine/Source/` and `Code/GameEngine/Include/`

```
GameEngine/
├── Source/
│   ├── Common/          # Shared utilities, game state, configuration
│   │   ├── Audio/
│   │   ├── Bezier/
│   │   ├── INI/         # Configuration file parsing
│   │   ├── RTS/         # High-level game concepts (Teams, Squads)
│   │   ├── System/      # Global managers (Radar, BuildAssistant, Upgrade)
│   │   └── Thing/       # Object templates and factories
│   │
│   ├── GameClient/      # Client-side simulation (UI, camera, input handling)
│   │   ├── Drawable/    # Visual representation layer
│   │   ├── GUI/         # Control bar, menus, UI callbacks
│   │   ├── Input/       # Keyboard/mouse input processing
│   │   ├── MessageStream/  # Message routing
│   │   ├── System/      # Display, particles, sounds
│   │   └── Terrain/     # Terrain visual system
│   │
│   ├── GameLogic/       # *** CORE GAME SIMULATION (CRITICAL FOR HEADLESS) ***
│   │   ├── AI/          # AI player logic, pathfinding, group management
│   │   ├── Object/      # Units, buildings, projectiles (Object class)
│   │   ├── Map/         # Terrain logic, triggers
│   │   ├── ScriptEngine/  # Map scripting (custom game logic)
│   │   └── System/      # GameLogic singleton, state management
│   │
│   ├── GameNetwork/     # Network multiplayer, command distribution
│   │   ├── GameSpy/     # Online matchmaking
│   │   └── WOLBrowser/  # Web browser integration
│   │
│   └── Precompiled/     # Precompiled headers
│
└── Include/
    ├── Common/          # Header files (parallel structure)
    ├── GameClient/
    ├── GameLogic/
    └── GameNetwork/
```

### Key Files in GameEngine

| File | Purpose | Location |
|------|---------|----------|
| **GameCommon.h** | **Frame rate & game constants** | `Include/Common/` |
| **GameEngine.h** | Main engine interface, `execute()` loop | `Include/Common/` |
| **GameLogic.h** | Game state manager, object registry | `Include/GameLogic/` |
| **Object.h** | Base entity class (units/buildings) | `Include/GameLogic/` |
| **Player.h** | Player state (money, power, supplies) | `Include/Common/` |
| **Money.h** | Resource tracking | `Include/Common/` |
| **PartitionManager.h** | Spatial partitioning & fog of war | `Include/GameLogic/` |
| **MessageStream.h** | Event/command propagation system | `Include/Common/` |
| **NetCommandMsg.h** | Multiplayer command serialization | `Include/GameNetwork/` |
| **UpdateModule.h** | Base class for unit/building behaviors | `Include/GameLogic/Module/` |

---

## 3. KEY SYSTEMS FOR HEADLESS ENGINE

### 3.1 Game Tick / Main Loop

**Frame Rate Definition:**
```cpp
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/Common/GameCommon.h (Line 66)
enum {
    LOGICFRAMES_PER_SECOND = 30,      // *** 30 FPS fixed tick rate ***
    MSEC_PER_SECOND = 1000
};
```

**Main Loop Entry Points:**

```cpp
// GameEngine class hierarchy:
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/Common/GameEngine.h

class GameEngine : public SubsystemInterface {
    void init(int argc, char *argv[]);     // Initialize
    void reset();                            // Reset to start state
    void execute();                          // Main loop (blocks until quit)
    void update();                           // Per-frame update
    void setFramesPerSecondLimit(Int fps);  // Cap FPS (default 45)
};
```

**Game Loop Architecture:**
1. `GameEngine::execute()` - Main loop (Win32-specific in `Win32GameEngine`)
2. Each frame:
   - `GameEngine::update()` calls
   - `GameLogic::update()` - Update all units/buildings
   - `GameClient::update()` - Update camera, input, UI
   - `Display::draw()` - Render scene
3. Loop continues until `GameEngine::getQuitting()` returns true

**File:** `Code/GameEngine/Source/Common/GameEngine.cpp`

**For headless operation:**
- Call `GameLogic::update()` directly in your own loop
- Stub out `GameClient` and `Display` initialization
- Use fixed 30 Hz tick rate (no frame-skipping sync needed)

---

### 3.2 Entity/Object System

**Base Class Hierarchy:**

```cpp
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/Common/Thing.h
class Thing : public MemoryPoolObject {
    // Base for all game entities
};

// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/GameLogic/Object.h (Line 154)
class Object : public Thing, public Snapshot {
    // *** MAIN ENTITY CLASS ***
    // All units, buildings, projectiles derive from this
};
```

**Object Structure:**

```cpp
class Object {
    // Identity
    ObjectID m_id;                    // Unique identifier
    ThingTemplate *m_template;        // Template data (from INI files)
    Player *m_owner;                  // Owner player
    Team *m_team;                     // Team affiliation

    // State
    Coord3D m_position;               // World position
    Real m_angle;                     // Facing angle (0-360 degrees)

    // Properties
    Int m_health;                     // Current health points
    VeterancyLevel m_veterancy;       // Rank (LEVEL_REGULAR, VETERAN, ELITE, HEROIC)
    ObjectStatusBits m_status;        // State flags (alive, moving, attacking, etc.)

    // Behavior System
    UpdateModule *m_updateModules[];  // Behavior modules (See Section 3.5)

    // Visibility
    ObjectShroudStatus m_shroudStatus; // Fog of war status (CLEAR, FOGGED, SHROUDED)
};

// Object types determined at creation:
enum ObjectKindOf {
    KINDOF_UNIT,              // Mobile combat unit
    KINDOF_STRUCTURE,         // Building
    KINDOF_PROJECTILE,        // Bullet, missile, etc.
    KINDOF_AIRCRAFT,          // Flying unit
    // ... ~50 more types
};
```

**Key Methods:**
- `getHealth()` / `takeDamage()` - Damage handling
- `setPosition()` / `getPosition()` - Location
- `getNextObject()` / Previous tracking for global iteration
- `CRC()` / `xfer()` - Serialization (for save/load)

**File:** `/Code/GameEngine/Include/GameLogic/Object.h`

---

### 3.3 Player State & Resources

**Player Class:**

```cpp
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/Common/Player.h

class Player : public Snapshot {
    // Identity
    PlayerIndex m_playerIndex;        // 0-15 (MAX_PLAYER_COUNT = 16)
    AsciiString m_playerName;
    AsciiString m_side;               // "USA", "China", "GLA"

    // Resources
    Money m_money;                    // Class in Money.h
    Int m_powerPoints;                // Power bar level (for power plants)

    // Army composition
    std::list<Object*> m_allObjects;  // All units/buildings owned by player

    // Science/Upgrades
    std::vector<Science> m_sciences;  // Technology researched
    std::vector<UpgradeTemplate*> m_upgrades; // Permanent upgrades

    // Special Powers
    SpecialPowerReadyTimer m_specialPowers[]; // Cooldowns for special abilities
};

// Money management
class Money {
    UnsignedInt m_money;              // Current amount
    UnsignedInt withdraw(amount, playSound);  // Spend money
    void deposit(amount, playSound);  // Receive money
};
```

**Power System:**
- Buildings: Power plants generate power
- Units: Some units consume power when active
- Power bar fluctuates based on generation vs. consumption
- **Critical:** Building placement can be restricted if insufficient power available

**Files:** 
- `Code/GameEngine/Include/Common/Player.h`
- `Code/GameEngine/Include/Common/Money.h`
- `Code/GameEngine/Include/Common/Energy.h` (power tracking)

---

### 3.4 Action Injection & Command System

**Command Flow Architecture:**

```
User Input / AI Decision
    ↓
MessageStream (client-side translation)
    ↓
CommandList (queued commands)
    ↓
GameLogic::processCommandList()
    ↓
Object::issueCommand() → UpdateModule execution
    ↓
Unit moves / attacks / builds
```

**GameMessage System:**

```cpp
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/Common/MessageStream.h

union GameMessageArgumentType {
    Int integer;
    Real real;
    ObjectID objectID;
    Coord3D location;
    // ... 11 total types
};

class GameMessage {
    enum Type {
        MSG_MOUSE_LEFT_CLICK,
        MSG_MOUSE_RIGHT_CLICK,
        MSG_RAW_KEY_DOWN,
        // ... ~200+ message types
    };

    Type m_type;
    GameMessageArgument *m_argList;  // Linked list of arguments
};
```

**Network Command Messages:**

```cpp
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/GameNetwork/NetCommandMsg.h

class NetCommandMsg {
    UnsignedInt m_executionFrame;     // When to execute (frame sync)
    UnsignedInt m_playerID;            // Which player
    NetCommandType m_commandType;     // Type of command (enum)
};

class NetGameCommandMsg : public NetCommandMsg {
    GameMessage *constructGameMessage();  // Convert to GameMessage
};
```

**For AI Integration:**

```cpp
// Inject unit move command:
Object *unit = gameLogic->findObjectByID(unitID);
unit->setPosition(newPosition);  // Direct manipulation
// OR
GameMessage msg;
msg.m_type = MSG_MOVE_UNIT;
msg.addArgument(ARGUMENTDATATYPE_OBJECTID, unitID);
msg.addArgument(ARGUMENTDATATYPE_LOCATION, targetLocation);
// Process through CommandList → GameLogic

// Inject attack command:
unit->setAttackTarget(targetObject);
```

**Key Files:**
- `Code/GameEngine/Include/Common/MessageStream.h` - Message definitions
- `Code/GameEngine/Include/GameNetwork/NetCommandMsg.h` - Network serialization
- `Code/GameEngine/Source/GameLogic/GameLogic.cpp` - `processCommandList()`
- `Code/GameEngine/Include/GameLogic/Object.h` - Command methods

---

### 3.5 Object Update/Behavior Module System

**Core Architecture:**

Objects don't have hardcoded behavior. Instead, they use a **modular component system**:

```cpp
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/GameLogic/Module/UpdateModule.h

class UpdateModuleInterface {
    virtual UpdateSleepTime update() = 0;   // Called each frame or when awoken
};

enum UpdateSleepTime {
    UPDATE_SLEEP_NONE = 1,           // Call every frame
    UPDATE_SLEEP_FOREVER = 0x3fffffff, // Never call until awakened
    // Custom: UPDATE_SLEEP(N) = N frames
};
```

**Module Examples:**

```
Object contains multiple UpdateModule instances:
├── PhysicsUpdate        → Movement, collision
├── AIUpdate            → Combat AI, pathfinding
├── WeaponUpdate        → Firing, cooldowns
├── DamageModule        → Health/armor
├── ProductionUpdate    → Building production (for factories)
├── LocomotorUpdate     → Walking/flying animation
└── ... ~100+ module types
```

**Update Schedule:**

```cpp
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/GameLogic/Module/UpdateModule.h

enum SleepyUpdatePhase {
    PHASE_INITIAL = 0,     // Resolve object creation/deletion
    PHASE_PHYSICS = 1,     // Physics updates (movement)
    PHASE_NORMAL = 2,      // Standard updates (combat, AI)
    PHASE_FINAL = 3,       // Cleanup and rendering updates
};

// Within GameLogic each frame:
for (frame 0 to N_frames) {
    // Phase 0: Create/delete objects
    for (each object) { if (object->isAwake()) update(PHASE_INITIAL); }

    // Phase 1: Physics
    for (each object) { if (object->isAwake()) update(PHASE_PHYSICS); }

    // Phase 2: Standard logic
    for (each object) { if (object->isAwake()) update(PHASE_NORMAL); }

    // Phase 3: Final (visual updates)
    for (each object) { if (object->isAwake()) update(PHASE_FINAL); }
}
```

**Files:**
- `Code/GameEngine/Include/GameLogic/Module/UpdateModule.h`
- `Code/GameEngine/Source/GameLogic/Object/` - 100+ module implementations

---

### 3.6 Fog of War / Shroud System

**PartitionManager:**

```cpp
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/GameLogic/PartitionManager.h

class PartitionManager {
    // Spatial grid for fast queries
    PartitionCell m_cells[GRID_WIDTH][GRID_HEIGHT];

    // Fog of War tracking
    struct CellShroudStatus {
        CELLSHROUD_CLEAR,     // Visible right now
        CELLSHROUD_FOGGED,    // Seen before, but not now
        CELLSHROUD_SHROUDED   // Never seen
    };
};

// Object shroud status
enum ObjectShroudStatus {
    OBJECTSHROUD_CLEAR,        // Fully visible
    OBJECTSHROUD_PARTIAL_CLEAR, // Partially visible
    OBJECTSHROUD_FOGGED,       // Visible in past, fogged now
    OBJECTSHROUD_SHROUDED      // Never been seen
};
```

**How Fog Works:**

1. Units have a "sight radius"
2. Each frame, PartitionManager calculates visible cells around units
3. Objects update their `m_shroudStatus` based on visibility
4. AI/Players can only target units they can see (depends on `m_shroudStatus`)

**For Headless Engine:**
- Shroud system is **critical for AI decision making**
- Must track per-player visibility (different AI players see different maps)
- Query methods:
  - `PartitionManager::getObjectsInRegion()` - Objects in area
  - `Object::getShroudStatus(player)` - Can player see this object?

**File:** `Code/GameEngine/Include/GameLogic/PartitionManager.h`

---

## 4. GAMEENGINEDEVICE (Rendering & Audio Layer)

### Directory Structure

```
GameEngineDevice/
├── Include/
│   ├── MilesAudioDevice/     # Miles Sound System audio
│   ├── VideoDevice/          # Video playback (Bink codec)
│   ├── W3DDevice/            # *** MAIN RENDERING LAYER (DirectX 9) ***
│   │   ├── Common/           # Conversion, utilities
│   │   ├── GameClient/       # Rendering subsystem
│   │   └── GameLogic/        # Physics visualization
│   └── Win32Device/          # Windows OS integration
│
├── Source/
│   ├── MilesAudioDevice/     # Audio playback
│   ├── VideoDevice/          # Video/cutscene playback
│   ├── W3DDevice/            # DirectX 9 rendering (WW3D engine)
│   └── Win32Device/          # Windows window, input hooks
│
└── [Libraries]/
    ├── DirectX9/             # DirectX 9.0c SDK
    ├── Miles6/               # Miles Sound System SDK
    └── Bink/                 # Bink Video SDK
```

### Key Components

**W3DDevice - Main Rendering Engine:**

```cpp
// File: Code/GameEngineDevice/Include/W3DDevice/GameClient/W3DDisplay.h

class W3DDisplay : public Display {
    // Virtual methods from Display interface:
    void draw();                  // Render scene
    void update();                // Update render state
    void drawLine(...);           // Debug drawing
    void drawFillRect(...);       // UI drawing

    // W3D-specific:
    void renderTerrain();         // Terrain mesh
    void renderObjects();         // Unit/building meshes
    void renderParticles();       // Particle effects
    void renderUI();              // Control bar, text
};
```

**Win32Device - OS Integration:**

```cpp
class Win32GameEngine : public GameEngine {
    // Creates W3DDisplay
    // Handles Windows messages (WM_PAINT, WM_SIZE, etc.)
    // Manages DirectX device reset on window focus loss
};
```

### Rendering Dependencies

**Tightly Coupled:**
- `GameClient` → `Display` (virtual interface, loose coupling!)
- `GameLogic` → `Drawable` objects (for visual effects sync)
- `GameLogic` has minimal rendering dependency

**Abstract Interface:**

```cpp
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/GameClient/Display.h

class Display : public SubsystemInterface {
    virtual void draw() = 0;                    // Pure virtual
    virtual void drawLine(...) = 0;
    virtual void drawFillRect(...) = 0;
    // ~20 pure virtual methods
};

// W3DDisplay implements Display interface
// Can be replaced with NullDisplay stub
```

### Headless Stub Strategy

**Option A: Null Rendering**
```cpp
// Create a NullDisplay : public Display
class NullDisplay : public Display {
    void draw() override {}           // No-op
    void drawLine(...) override {}    // No-op
    void drawFillRect(...) override {} // No-op
    // ... all methods = no-op
};

// Inject in engine initialization:
gameEngine->createDisplay() → new NullDisplay()
```

**Option B: Network Streaming**
```cpp
// Create a RemoteDisplay : public Display
class RemoteDisplay : public Display {
    void draw() override {
        // Send screen state to client via network/IPC
    }
};
```

**Option C: Headless Variant**
```cpp
// Build separate libGameEngineHeadless.lib
// Exclude W3DDevice/Win32Device entirely
// Link with GameEngine + GameLogic only
```

**Files to Stub:**
- `Code/GameEngineDevice/Source/W3DDevice/` - All rendering
- `Code/GameEngineDevice/Source/MilesAudioDevice/` - Audio
- `Code/GameEngineDevice/Source/VideoDevice/` - Video cutscenes
- `Code/Main/WinMain.cpp` - Windows message loop

